comment.narrative:
1.1	Insufficient effectiveness of implementation nationally adopted HCFC phase-out strategies
1.2	Cooperation between non-Art 5 countries on effective action standards is minimal or absent and regional networking with other partner countries in the region is lacking which prevents information and experience exchange
2.1	HCFCs are not re-used domestically due to absence of a comprehensive HCFC re-use systems, and country depends on imports;
2.2	Gaps in regulatory and institutional frameworks resulted in unconstrained import of HCFC based equipment that creates long-term demand for HCFCs
2.3	Lack of portable HCFC analytical equipment and instrumentation
2.4	Continued illegal trade in ODS and mislabelling of container
3.1	Lack of current information products and programs in the servicing sector on alternatives to HCFCs in refrigerated equipment;
3.2	Low awareness on new alternative technologies in the servicing sector and benefits in energy savings (co-benefits for economic operations as well as for climate change)
4.1	Refrigerated equipment continues to be manufactured and maintained with the use of HCFCs;
4.2	Weak basic servicing tooling of staff responsible for maintenance of railway fleet and high refrigerant emissions due to transport and use specifics;
4.3	Lack of integration of ODS disposal into HCFC re-use system to complete ODS management cycle at national level
5.1	Lack of participatory mechanisms;

